{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17644412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17644412"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:05:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:05:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18045"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18045"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10759"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73366"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10759"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18045"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58838"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"10200"},{"type":"tags","id":"10201"},{"type":"tags","id":"10203"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25099"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25107"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73366"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a histological difference between osteoblasts and osteoclasts?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Osteoblasts have large extensions called canaliculi whereas osteoclasts don\u0027t","Osteoblasts are larger than osteoclasts","Osteoclasts are larger than osteoblasts","Osteoblasts are multinucleated whereas osteoclasts are mononucleated","Osteoblasts are trapped within bone"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoclasts are larger than osteoblasts\u003C/strong\u003E and are multinucleated cells responsible for bone resorption. In contrast, osteoblasts are smaller, mononucleated cells that are involved in bone formation. These histological differences are key in identifying their distinct roles in bone metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoblasts are larger than osteoclasts\u003C/strong\u003E - Osteoclasts are actually larger and multinucleated\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoblasts are multinucleated whereas osteoclasts are mononucleated\u003C/strong\u003E - Osteoclasts are multinucleated, not osteoblasts\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoblasts are trapped within bone\u003C/strong\u003E - Osteoblasts can become trapped and differentiate into osteocytes, but this is not a histological feature distinguishing them from osteoclasts\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoblasts have large extensions called canaliculi whereas osteoclasts don\u0027t\u003C/strong\u003E - Canaliculi are extensions of osteocytes, not osteoblasts\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Osteoclasts are larger and multinucleated cells responsible for bone resorption.","Osteoblasts are smaller, mononucleated cells involved in bone formation.","Histological differences between osteoblasts and osteoclasts help in identifying their distinct roles in bone metabolism."],"references":["Gartner, L. P. (2020). Textbook of histology e-book: Textbook of histology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Baig MA, Bacha D. Histology, Bone. 2023 May 1. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31082176","Blumer MJF. Bone tissue and histological and molecular events during development of the long bones. Ann Anat. 2021 May;235:151704. doi: 10.1016/j.aanat.2021.151704. Epub 2021 Feb 16. PMID: 33600952","Florencio-Silva R, Sasso GR, Sasso-Cerri E, Sim\u00f5es MJ, Cerri PS. Biology of Bone Tissue: Structure, Function, and Factors That Influence Bone Cells. Biomed Res Int. 2015;2015:421746. doi: 10.1155/2015/421746. Epub 2015 Jul 13. PMID: 26247020; PMCID: PMC4515490"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58838"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18045"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58838"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T11:57:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T21:18:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10759"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73366"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}}